all right. here's the thing. encryption is real. it really is beyond anyone to brute force it. we know this because encryption protocols are open to the public and are continuously being challenged and that this is exactly the proof of its strength. the biggest mistake anyone can make regarding encryption is keeping it private. germany did this with enigma and lost everything for it. why? because there wasn't an army of dedicated hackers determined to find its flaws and take it down as quickly as it should have been; by keeping it closed, when an actual hacker outside did attack it, he won and relatively quickly. had germany allowed the world to freely test it, it would have crumbled even faster and the result would have been where we are today--with unbreakable encryption. 



